SUMMARIZER="J">

Chancellor of the Exchequer John Major, 47, will succeed his mentor, Margaret Thatcher, 
as Britain's prime minister. Major, a high-school dropout, was elected Conservative Party 
leader after Thatcher, failing to garner the necessary majority votes in a leadership 
contest last Tuesday, resigned. 

Though Major was two votes short of the required majority in yesterday's election, he 
was elected leader of the ruling Conservative Party after his challengers, former Defense 
Secretary Heseltine and Foreign Secretary Hurd, conceded defeat. 

The Labor Party, just recently a strong favorite in the next election, is now in second 
place behind a Tory party led by Major.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d120"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP901127-0119"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="J">

John Major, 47, Margaret Thatcher's protege, was elected Conservative Party leader 
Tuesday night and will succeed her as prime minister. 

Mrs. Thatcher, ending 11 years in power, intended to submit her resignation to Queen 
Elizabeth II on Wednesday. Major would then be called to lead the government. 

His election climaxed a tumultuous month for the Conservative Party. The party trailed 
the Labor Party in the polls and lost a string of local Parliamentary elections. On Nov. 1, 
Deputy Prime Minister, Sir Geoffrey Howe resigned in a policy dispute over the 
European Community, calling Mrs. Thatcher a threat to Britain's vital interests.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d120"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA122190-0149"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="J">

In four television interviews that began airing today, British Prime Minister John Major, 
said all Iraqi troops must withdraw from Kuwait or they will be "forcibly removed." 
Major arrived in Washington Thursday night for on a three-day visit to the U.S. He and 
President Bush will hold discussions this evening at Camp David in Maryland where they 
will spend the night.

Major's stance on Iraq was as unyielding as that of his predecessor, Margaret Thatcher, 
but unlike Mrs. Thatcher, he was polite to reporters questioning him. Comparing Major 
and Thatcher, one U.S. official said, "The biggest change is personal style."</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d120"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FBIS3-1707"
