SUMMARIZER="J">

On Easter Sunday, three Cabinet ministers supported John Major in the wake of 
speculation that he could be forced out this autumn. Both Secretary of State for Education 
John Patten and Michael Howard, the Home Secretary, dismissed talk of a leadership 
contest before the next general election. Lord Wakeham, Leader of the House of Lords, 
called on Torries to be loyal to Mr. Major.

One poll shows that Michael Heseltine is the favorite to replace Mr. Major if he is forced 
out, but that Michael Portillo will vigorously campaign to secure Eurosceptic policies 
from the eventual winner.</SUM> 

<SUM
DOCSET="d120"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FBIS4-24776"
SELECTOR="I"
SUMMARIZER="J">

In local elections across Britain yesterday, the Conservatives suffered their worst defeat 
ever, losing 444 seats. They are now the third party nationally.

Some anti-John Major Conservatives are happy about the defeat. Propelled to power by 
Margaret Thatcher who expected to continue her program discretely, Major is a weak 
leader. Though some pushed him to pursue new "leftist" policies, Major vacillates to the 
left and to the right, producing a "crisis of honor."

He lacks vision, is incompetent on domestic and international issues, and is a political 
blunderer. The Tories will make him a scapegoat for their defeat at the polls.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d120"
TYPE="PERDOC"
